## Data Type 2
# In a previous data type we will introduce data type like string,integer,float but
in this lecture we will introduce one more data type called boolean.And also learn
about Type conversion.
a = 10
b = 1.1
c = 'India'
d = True
e = False
print(type(a))                          <class'int'>
print(type(b))                          <class'float'>
print(type(c))                          <class'str'>
print(type(d))                          <class'bool'>
print(type(e))                          <class'bool'>
Notice carefully,the letter T in True and letter F in false
has to be capital otherwise it not not to be considered as Boolean.
As we are studied four data type let us tried some different, 
Which is called Data Conversion from one data type to another
a = int(5.7)
b = int('10')
print(a,type(a))                         5 <class'int'>
print(b,type(b))                        10 <class'int'>

a = str(5)
b = str(5.5)
print(a,type(a))                         5 <class'str'>
print(b,type(b))                        5.5 <class'str'>

a = float(7)
b = float('9')
print(a,type(a))                         7.0 <class'float'>
print(b,type(b))                        10.0 <class'float'>
# How type conversion in boolean data type:
 let us try to convert integer to boolean data type
a = bool(10)                             
b = bool(0)                             
c = bool(-10)   
print(a,type(a))                         True <class'bool'>
print(b,type(b))                        False <class'bool'>
print(c,type(c))                         True <class'bool'>
listen carefully, That is because whenever computer converts an integer to boolean,
all values except 0 are consider as True whereas 0 is only value which will give us
Boolean representation is False.
# Now, let us try the similiar thing with a floating point value.
a = bool(10.0)                             
b = bool(0.0)                             
c = bool(-10.0)   
print(a,type(a))                         True <class'bool'>
print(b,type(b))                        False <class'bool'>
print(c,type(c))                         True <class'bool'>
# Now let us try with some more examples, Here 0 is niether a integer nor float number 
 here is it string and string representation of boolean data type is always True 
 except one condition. Let us see what the condition is. 
a = bool('India')
b = bool('10')
c = bool('10.1')
d = bool('0')
e = bool('')
print(a,Type(a))                         True <class'bool'>         
print(b,Type(b))                         True <class'bool'>
print(c,Type(c))                         True <class'bool'>
print(d,Type(d))                         True <class'bool'>
print(e,Type(e))                        False <class'bool'>  # NOTICE CAREFULLY
let us only one condition e is equal to boolean of empty string,
which means empty string and a boolean conversion of empty string is false.
